---

ğŸ”¹ 1ï¸âƒ£ Enable FlatLaf window decorations (already OK)

Make sure this exists before frame creation (static block):

UIManager.put("TitlePane.useWindowDecorations", true);


---

ğŸ”¹ 2ï¸âƒ£ Add DISTINCT TITLE BAR COLORS (KEY STEP)

âœ… Use FlatClientProperties on JRootPane

Add this method to your class:

import com.formdev.flatlaf.FlatClientProperties;

private void setupTitleBarStyle() {

    // Gradient title bar (different from content background)
    getRootPane().putClientProperty(
            FlatClientProperties.TITLE_BAR_BACKGROUND,
            new Color[]{
                    new Color(60, 63, 65),   // darker top
                    new Color(43, 43, 43)    // darker bottom
            }
    );

    // Title text color
    getRootPane().putClientProperty(
            FlatClientProperties.TITLE_BAR_FOREGROUND,
            new Color(220, 220, 220)
    );

    // Add bottom divider line (IMPORTANT for separation)
    getRootPane().putClientProperty(
            FlatClientProperties.TITLE_BAR_BORDER,
            BorderFactory.createMatteBorder(0, 0, 1, 0,
                    new Color(90, 90, 90))
    );
}


---

ğŸ”¹ 3ï¸âƒ£ Call it from constructor (VERY IMPORTANT)

public AccessCheckerApp() {
    setTitle("Access Checker");
    setSize(960, 540);
    setResizable(false);
    setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
    setLocationRelativeTo(null);

    setupTitleBarStyle();   // ğŸ‘ˆ add this BEFORE initUI()

    initUI();
}


---

ğŸ”¹ 4ï¸âƒ£ (Optional but recommended) Slightly different content background

To further separate title bar from body, give the main panel a slightly different background:

Inside initUI():

JPanel panel = new JPanel(null);
panel.setBackground(new Color(37, 37, 38)); // content background
setContentPane(panel);

This is exactly how IntelliJ / VS Code does it.


